{"schema_version": 2, "source_hash": "53dae54a23ad3115", "candidate": {"id": "cand-005", "name": "Dr. James Caldwell", "raw_cv": "DR. JAMES CALDWELL\njames.caldwell@email.com | Cambridge, UK\n\nML ENGINEER\n\nPROFESSIONAL SUMMARY\nApplied ML engineer with 6 years of experience in computer vision and sensor fusion systems for defence and public safety applications. Active DV clearance holder. Expert in Python, PyTorch, and model deployment pipelines.\n\nEXPERIENCE\n\nML Engineer \u2014 QinetiQ, Malvern/Cambridge (2020\u2013present)\n- Designed and trained convolutional and transformer-based perception models for airborne EO/IR sensors\n- Led integration of ONNX-optimised models into embedded inference systems (NVIDIA Jetson)\n- Developed MLflow experiment tracking framework adopted across 3 project teams\n- Collaborated with signal processing team on radar-optical sensor fusion pipeline\n\nResearch Scientist (Computer Vision) \u2014 AWE, Aldermaston (2018\u20132020)\n- Developed object detection models for nuclear facility surveillance systems\n- Published one classified technical report and one open paper on domain adaptation\n\nSKILLS\nPython, PyTorch, ONNX, TensorRT, MLflow, OpenCV, NumPy, Git, Docker, Kubernetes (basic), C++ (basic), CUDA\n\nEDUCATION\nPhD Computer Vision \u2014 University of Edinburgh (2014\u20132018)\nMEng Electronics \u2014 University of Cambridge (2010\u20132014)\n\nCLEARANCE\nActive DV clearance (UK government)\n\nRIGHT TO WORK\nBritish citizen", "raw_linkedin": "Applied ML engineer with six years building perception systems for defence and public safety. I work at the intersection of deep learning and real-world deployment \u2014 training models that need to work reliably in the field, not just on benchmarks. Active DV clearance. Cambridge-based and comfortable with hybrid working arrangements. I care about hard problems with real stakes and prefer small, technically excellent teams. Open to senior ML engineer roles in defence, public safety, or aerospace.", "raw_interview_transcript": "Interviewer: James, thanks for coming in. Tell me about the perception work you've been doing at QinetiQ.\n\nJames: Sure. The core of my current role is developing and productionising perception models for airborne systems \u2014 mainly EO/IR cameras. We use PyTorch for training and then export to ONNX for deployment on embedded hardware. Latency and power constraints are real, so I've done a lot of model quantisation and TensorRT optimisation. Most recently I've been working on a sensor fusion system that combines radar and optical detections, which is quite an interesting problem.\n\nInterviewer: And your clearance status?\n\nJames: I hold active DV clearance, which I've maintained since my time at AWE. It's current.\n\nInterviewer: The role is 2 days in Cambridge, remote otherwise. How do you feel about that?\n\nJames: That works well. I live in Cambridge so the commute is easy. And I actually appreciate the flexibility \u2014 I tend to do my best deep work at home.\n\nInterviewer: Are you interested in the compressed hours option we offer?\n\nJames: Possibly down the line, but it's not a requirement for me. Standard hours are fine.\n\nInterviewer: Salary expectations?\n\nJames: I'm at \u00a388,000 at QinetiQ. Given the DV clearance I'd be expecting \u00a395\u2013100,000.", "years_experience": 6.0, "skills": ["Python", "PyTorch", "ONNX", "TensorRT", "MLflow", "OpenCV", "NumPy", "Git", "Docker", "Kubernetes", "C++", "CUDA", "Computer Vision", "Model Deployment", "Sensor Fusion", "Object Detection", "Domain Adaptation", "Model Quantisation"], "industries": ["Defence", "Public Safety", "Aerospace"], "seniority_level": "senior", "management_experience": true, "education_level": "phd", "career_trajectory": "ascending", "interview_score": 0.5, "culture_fit_score": 0.5, "constraints": [{"id": "ef186ae0", "type": "hard", "side": "candidate", "category": "clearance", "description": "Holds active DV clearance; requires roles 